&lt;p&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Concept&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Lens are of two types:
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Concave Lens or diverging lens&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Convex Lens or converging lens&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;When a light ray falls on a concave or convex lenses obliquely at its optical centre, it continues to follow its path.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;When &lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;a light ray falls&lt;/span&gt; parallel to the principal axis on&amp;nbsp;concave or convex lenses, the reflected ray passes through a focus (F) on the principal axis.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;When &lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;a light ray &lt;/span&gt;passing through focus strikes concave or convex lenses, the reflected ray will pass parallel to the principal axis.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Convex lens always forms real image while concave always forms virtual image.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Explanation:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;When the object is placed at the focus of the convex lens then the image formed will be larger in size, real &amp;amp; is&lt;strong&gt; located at infinity&lt;/strong&gt; as we can see in the ray diagram given below.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;//storage.googleapis.com/tb-img/production/23/03/F1_Savita_Defence_28-3-23_D12.png&quot; style=&quot;width: 271px; height: 152px;&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Here &amp;#39;F&amp;#39; denotes focus, &amp;#39;C&amp;#39; denotes centre of curvature&amp;nbsp;&amp;amp; AB is height of the object.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&amp;nbsp;The nature of the image is decided by the magnification (M) of the lens,&amp;nbsp;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(M = {v \over u}\)&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp; ; where v is the image distance &amp;amp; u is object distance.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Lens formula&amp;nbsp;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\( {1 \over v}-{1 \over u} = {1 \over f}\)&lt;/span&gt;; where f is focal length of the lens.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Focal length of convex lens is always positive &amp;amp; for concave lens is negative.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Since object is real, so object distance is taken as negative.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Concept&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The sign convention for radii of curvature in optics is an essential concept here.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;table border=&quot;1&quot;&gt;
	&lt;tbody style=&quot;margin: 0px; padding: 0px; outline: 0px;&quot;&gt;
		&lt;tr style=&quot;margin: 0px; padding: 0px; outline: 0px; background-color: (250, 250, 250);&quot;&gt;
			&lt;td style=&quot;margin: 0px; padding: 6px 13px; outline: 0px; border-top: none; border-right-color: (208, 215, 222); border-bottom-color: (208, 215, 222); border-left: none; border-image: initial;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Lens Type&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
			&lt;td style=&quot;margin: 0px; padding: 6px 13px; outline: 0px; border-top: none; border-right-color: (208, 215, 222); border-bottom-color: (208, 215, 222); border-left-color: (208, 215, 222); border-image: initial;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Center of Curvature Position&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
			&lt;td style=&quot;margin: 0px; padding: 6px 13px; outline: 0px; border-top: none; border-right: none; border-bottom-color: (208, 215, 222); border-left-color: (208, 215, 222); border-image: initial;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The radius of Curvature (R)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
		&lt;/tr&gt;
		&lt;tr style=&quot;margin: 0px; padding: 0px; outline: 0px; background-color: (250, 250, 250);&quot;&gt;
			&lt;td style=&quot;margin: 0px; padding: 6px 13px; outline: 0px; border-top-color: (208, 215, 222); border-right-color: (208, 215, 222); border-bottom-color: (208, 215, 222); border-left: none; border-image: initial;&quot;&gt;Double Convex&lt;/td&gt;
			&lt;td style=&quot;margin: 0px; padding: 6px 13px; outline: 0px; border-color: (208, 215, 222); border-image: initial;&quot;&gt;The opposite side of light&lt;/td&gt;
			&lt;td style=&quot;margin: 0px; padding: 6px 13px; outline: 0px; border-top-color: (208, 215, 222); border-right: none; border-bottom-color: (208, 215, 222); border-left-color: (208, 215, 222); border-image: initial;&quot;&gt;Positive&lt;/td&gt;
		&lt;/tr&gt;
		&lt;tr style=&quot;margin: 0px; padding: 0px; outline: 0px; background-color: (250, 250, 250);&quot;&gt;
			&lt;td style=&quot;margin: 0px; padding: 6px 13px; outline: 0px; border-top-color: (208, 215, 222); border-right-color: (208, 215, 222); border-bottom: none; border-left: none; border-image: initial;&quot;&gt;Double Concave&lt;/td&gt;
			&lt;td style=&quot;margin: 0px; padding: 6px 13px; outline: 0px; border-top-color: (208, 215, 222); border-right-color: (208, 215, 222); border-bottom: none; border-left-color: (208, 215, 222); border-image: initial;&quot;&gt;Same side as light&lt;/td&gt;
			&lt;td style=&quot;margin: 0px; padding: 6px 13px; outline: 0px; border-top-color: (208, 215, 222); border-right: none; border-bottom: none; border-left-color: (208, 215, 222); border-image: initial;&quot;&gt;Negative&lt;/td&gt;
		&lt;/tr&gt;
	&lt;/tbody&gt;
&lt;/table&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;For lenses, the radius of curvature, R, is considered positive if the corresponding center of curvature is on the side of the lens from which the light emerges (opposite the side of the incoming light), and negative if it is on the same side as the incoming light.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;A double convex lens is a lens that is curved outward on both sides.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The light enters one curved side, exits the other, and both centers of curvature are on the side opposite the incoming light.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;https://i.stack.imgur.com/AExYS.gif&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Explanation&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Given the sign convention, when we look at a double convex lens, the radius of curvature for the first surface (R1) is positive because its center of curvature is on the side from which the light emerges.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Similarly, for the second surface (R2), the center of curvature is also on the side from which the light enters&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Therefore, R2 is negative.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;So, for a double convex lens,&amp;nbsp;R1 is positive and R2 is negative.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The sign convention is a crucial part of working with lenses and mirrors in optics.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;It helps in accurately predicting the characteristics of the image formed, such as whether the image is real or virtual, upright or inverted, and its position and size.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The radii of curvature, R1, and R2, along with the refractive index of the lens material, determine the focal length of the lens according to the lensmaker&amp;#39;s formula.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Understanding the sign convention is essential for calculating the properties of lenses.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;For a double concave lens, where both surfaces curve inward, the sign convention would result in both radii of curvature being negative.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is&amp;nbsp;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Concave lens&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Myopia&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;is a disease in which the patient &lt;strong&gt;cannot see distant objects clearly&lt;/strong&gt;.&amp;nbsp;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;In myopia,&amp;nbsp;the eyeball is too long for the normal focusing power of the eye. As a result,&amp;nbsp;images of distant objects appear blurred.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The nearsighted&amp;nbsp;(myopic)&amp;nbsp;eye&amp;nbsp;converges rays from a distant object in front of the retina;&amp;nbsp;thus, they are diverging when they strike the retina, producing a&amp;nbsp;blurry image.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;A&amp;nbsp;concave lens&amp;nbsp;(minus powered) is&amp;nbsp;placed in front of a myopic eye&lt;/strong&gt;,&amp;nbsp;moving the image back to the retina and clarifying the image.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Far-sightedness:&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;​Hypermetropia&amp;nbsp;is a condition in which the individual&amp;nbsp;can focus only on faraway objects&amp;nbsp;which is why it is called&amp;nbsp;long-sightedness or&amp;nbsp;Far-sightedness.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It can be corrected by a convex lens (converging lens).&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Presbyopia:​&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The&amp;nbsp;power of accommodation of the eye decreases&amp;nbsp;with ageing.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;People with the defect&amp;nbsp;can&amp;#39;t see nearby as well as distant objects distinctly.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Thus, we can say that myopia and hypermetropia both occur simultaneously.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Astigmatism:​&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;This is an eye defect in which a&amp;nbsp;blurred image is formed on the&amp;nbsp;retina.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It can be corrected by using spectacles, contact lenses, or by undergoing surgery.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

The correct answer is&amp;nbsp;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;an&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;interference of light.&lt;br /&gt;
CONCEPT:&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;When light shines onto a bubble it seems to change colour.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Not like those seen during a rainbow, which arises from differential refraction, the &lt;strong&gt;colours are seen during a soap bubble &lt;/strong&gt;that arises from&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;interference of light reflecting off the front and back surfaces of the thin film&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot; list-style-type: disc;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Interference&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;is a natural phenomenon that happens at every place and at every moment.

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Interference is the phenomenon in which two waves superpose to form the&amp;nbsp;resultant wave of the lower, higher, or same amplitude.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The most commonly seen interference is an&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;optical interference or&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;light interference&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;This is because light waves are randomly generated every which way by most sources.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;This means that light waves coming out of a source do not have a constant amplitude, frequency, or phase.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The most common example of interference of light is the soap bubble which reflects wide colours when illuminated by a light source.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot; list-style-type: disc;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Scattering&lt;/span&gt;, in physics, is a change in the direction of motion of a particle because of a collision with another particle.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In optics,&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;dispersion&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;is the phenomenon in which the phase velocity of a wave depends on its frequency.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Polarization&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;is a property applying to transverse waves that specify the geometrical orientation of the oscillations.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

The correct option is a&amp;nbsp;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;convex mirror.&lt;br /&gt;
EXPLANATION:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;strong&gt;Convex mirror:&lt;/strong&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;These are the spherical mirror that is curved outward and the image obtained is virtual, diminished, and erect for a real object.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Commonly used as rear-view (wing) mirrors in vehicles.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Convex mirrors are used in automobiles because they give an upright (not inverted), though diminished (smaller) image and provide a wider field of view as they are curved outwards. However, they don&amp;rsquo;t provide correct distant perception.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The outside rear-view mirror of modern automobiles is marked with the warning objects in the mirror being closer than they appear.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;These mirrors are fitted on the sides of the vehicle, enabling the driver to see traffic behind him/her to facilitate safe driving.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;It enables the driver to view a much larger area than would be possible with a plane mirror.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;In big showrooms and departmental stores, convex mirrors are used to have a view of the customers entering in as well as going out.&lt;strong&gt;​&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
Concave mirrors:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;These are the spherical mirror that is curved inward and the image obtained from these mirrors depend on the placement of the object.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&amp;nbsp;Used in torches, searchlights, and vehicle headlights to get powerful parallel beams of light.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;As shaving mirrors to see a larger image of the face.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The dentists use concave mirrors to see large images of the teeth of patients.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Large concave mirrors are used to concentrate sunlight to produce heat in a solar furnace.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Plane mirror:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The images formed from a plane mirror are the reflected images in their normal proportions but reversed from left to right. These are the most widely used mirrors.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
